<br>
Secondly, a smattering of random thoughts on the subject, sorry they won`t be in any sort of cohesive order.<br>
<br>
1. I am afraid to tell you that it is practically impossible to get a work visa without a college degree.  (save for some exceedingly rare and specialized cases).  Period.  So if you want to work in Japan, you`re either gonna have to do it under the table (probably not best if you`re planning on living there for any super extended amount of time) or else get a college degree.<br>
<br>
2. GED is not gonna help you out when it comes to applying to Japanese colleges directly.  Every one I`ve ever heard of (and every one that offers electrical engineering/Quantum physics) requires a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>high school degree </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and nearly always require a GPA higher than 2.0.<br>
<br>
3. Which leaves the following option open - going to uni in the US, then transferring.  Definitely do-able.  Even if you`re going to KSU, you can still apply to a wide host of other university exchange programs.  One thing - I don`t want to be mean, but you`ll definitely need higher than a 2.0 in college if you want to go on any exchange programs.  Usually you need at least a 3.0 and more often than not, a 3.5 (for good schools).  So make sure to keep you grades up.<br>
<br>
4. On a random note, I am assuming you speak fluent Japanese?  Because otherwise, it will be .... errrmm... rough.  I have a certificate in &quot;technical japanese&quot; (the translation of engineering and physics related texts) and I can tell you from personal experience that unless you have an excellent grasp of japanese, it will be nearly impossible for you to take engineering classes in japanese (or any college courses, for that matter) - which is a critical point, since no university in Japan offers degree instruction in the engineering field in english.  You will need to know Japanese as it will all be in Japanese - I would advise that you should be able to pass at least level 2 on the proficiency exam - and preferably level 1.  I had a teacher for my tech. japanese classes who was kind enough to provide glossaries for some of the more difficult words, and even then I spent hours banging my head against the wall!<br>
<br>
5. On the other hand, assuming you speak Japanese (not neccessarily fluently), are truely interested in Japan, are majoring in electrical engineer/quantum physics AND maintain good grades in college..... then I have the answer to all your dreams.<br>
<br>
The United States government maintains a program known as &quot;The National Security Education Program&quot; (NSEP) which provides practically full ride scholarships for students <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>majoring in fields of interest to national security</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> - one of which is most definitely engineering/quantum physics.  The purpose of this scholarship is to send such students abroad to specific countries of interest (of which Japan is one) in order to broaden their horizons/background etc. and to provide a base of highly-educated individuals with experience in foreign countries which can be drawn upon by the US government for any future needs.  If you can get one of these scholarships (and if you meet the above criteria, you are very very likely to) then it is an excellent opportunity which I suggest you take - there is a price, of course - after graduation you owe the US government 1 year of service (which is not at all a bad thing - you may very well find yourself working in Japan, and of course, you`ll be doing something related to your major).  I wanted to apply to this program, but decided to go ahead and graduate instead (hey, I was getting old)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.iie.org/Template.cfm?&amp;Template=/programs/nsep/default.htm" target="top">the direct link</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Anyway, as for the rest of your questions.<br>
<br>
a. Free plane ticket to Japan - yes, maybe if you get lucky, go on a  particularly lucrative exchange program, win the Japanese embassy`s speech contest (held once a year, the top prize per district is a free round trip ticket to Japan, inquire at your local consulate), participate in the JET program (more about this later - but you`ll need a college degree to apply).  But a free cross-pacific ticket is exceedingly rare, so don`t hold your breath waiting.  On the plus side, round trip tickets to japan can be had for under 800 US now-a-days, so it`s definitely do-able.<br>
<br>
b. VISA cost - visa`s are not &quot;bought&quot; persay (unless you are entering under the &quot;self-supporting&quot; visa-status, which is a non-issue as you need to be filthy rich to do so) - they are issued at the cruel whim of Japanese immigrations.  Details of the various japanese visas are available on line (too lazy to look up the links now) but the long and short of it - most americans get an automatic 90 day tourist visa upon disembarking in japan - it for all intents and purposes non-renewable (though it can be illegally extended by a quick jaunt to HK/s.korea - but immigrations tends to catch on after you do it more than once) - and you can`t work with it.  Student visas are available if you can find a school which will sponsor you.  I don`t think you can work persay - but you can have small jobs on campus if i`m not mistaken.  Everything else, you essentially need a university degree for.<br>
<br>
c. apartments are mad expensive, especially in tokyo.  But it`s the deposit/key money/realtor`s charge/deposit that will kill you.  In tokyo?  I`d estimate you`ll have to drop close to $3500-$5000 right of the bat, of which you`ll probably see maybe $500 back.   yeah, 500.  When I lived in Tokyo, I lived in a sh-t hole of a gaijin-house, (well, not thaaaat bad, really) but my rent was $800 US or so, for a tiny windowless room with no telephone, no lock on the door, no closet (no nothing!) sharing facilities with 10 other people.  Oh yeah, plus utilities.  Now, I lived fairly close to downtown, so that had something to do with it, but still....  You can probably make do in a so-called &quot;gaijin house&quot; for around $500-600 US per month on the outskirts of tokyo, but the commuting costs will kill you, though at least you don`t have to drop the key money/realtor charge, etc.  if you`re really interested, i wrote a post about living in Japan a few pages back (sorry, you`ll have to search for it yourself!  running out of time here!)  Anyway, if you only want to do it for 3-4 months as you said, I`d say go with the gaijin house option, and plan on at least $2000 for the 4 months.<br>
<br>
d. What kind of non-english teaching jobs specifically are you referring to? Anyway, unless you have a highly specialized skill (i.e scientist/web designer, etc.), can speak japanese fluently and have the above mentioned college degree/work visa, there really aren`t any non-english-teaching jobs out there.  Yeah.  that about sums it up.  Economy is really crappy right now too, which doesn`t help...<br>
<br>
Anyway, another thing to add is that the JET program will get you over to Japan, set you up with a (generally english-teaching related, though there are others available for those fluent in Japanese) job (usually working at an actual school - like a high school, as opposed to a language school), relatively high salary, a three year visa <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>and</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> generally take good care of you.  The catch is that it is somewhat competitive (not too bad) and of course, requires a university degree.  You can find details of it online. <br>
<br>
Finally, I hope this post was somewhat helpful to you.  I hope I didn`t sound too pessimistic - I just want people to know what they`re in for when they come to Japan - you sort of have to be prepared or else you can end up quite disapointed and disillusioned.  Sorry for the ton of spelling errors - I`m sleepy!!  Furthermore, I only addressed your question of working/studying in Japan - if you want to go to Japan on exchange, then the other programs will provide a good means for you to do that and don`t require a uni degree, etc.<br>
<br>
Anyway, hope that helps!<br>
<br>
Ganbatte!!<br>
